<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,546,1615]" pageId="6" pageNumber="561">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1410,1435]" pageId="6" pageNumber="561">Remarks.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[321,577,1411,1435]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Aereniphaula" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="561" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bandana" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[321,577,1411,1435]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="561">Aereniphaula bandana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[584,673,1410,1435]" pageId="6" pageNumber="561" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[584,673,1410,1435]" pageId="6" pageNumber="561">sp. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
differs from 
<taxonomicName box="[820,999,1411,1435]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Aereniphaula" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="561" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="machadorum">
<emphasis box="[820,999,1411,1435]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="561">A. machadorum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the upper eye lobes which are wellseparated, distance between them twice the width of each upper lobe (
<figureCitation box="[940,1009,1446,1471]" captionStart="FIGURES 4 – 10. 4 – 7" captionStartId="7.[151,264,1598,1620]" captionTargetBox="[151,1434,176,1573]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[151,1436,157,1577]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 4 – 10. 4 – 7, Aereniphaula bandana sp. nov., holotype, male, 4, dorsal view, 5, ventral view, 6, lateral view, 7, detail of head and pronotum; 8, Aereniphaula machadorum, detail of head and pronotum; 9 – 10, detail of metatarsomere I, 9, Aereniphaula bandana sp. nov., 10, Aereniphaula machadorum." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/265667/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="561">
Fig. 
<number box="[993,1009,1447,1471]" pageId="6" pageNumber="561" value="7.0">7</number>
</figureCitation>
); the anterior margin of prothorax 
<number box="[1400,1410,1447,1471]" pageId="6" pageNumber="561" value="1.0">1</number>
/ 
<number box="[1422,1436,1447,1471]" pageId="6" pageNumber="561" value="3.0">3</number>
wider than posterior margin; metatarsomere 
<date box="[672,704,1483,1507]" pageId="6" pageNumber="561">
I 
<number box="[693,704,1483,1507]" pageId="6" pageNumber="561" value="1.0">1</number>
</date>
/ 
<number box="[715,729,1483,1507]" pageId="6" pageNumber="561" value="3.0">3</number>
longer than II–III combined (
<figureCitation box="[1087,1160,1482,1507]" captionStart="FIGURES 4 – 10. 4 – 7" captionStartId="7.[151,264,1598,1620]" captionTargetBox="[151,1434,176,1573]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[151,1436,157,1577]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 4 – 10. 4 – 7, Aereniphaula bandana sp. nov., holotype, male, 4, dorsal view, 5, ventral view, 6, lateral view, 7, detail of head and pronotum; 8, Aereniphaula machadorum, detail of head and pronotum; 9 – 10, detail of metatarsomere I, 9, Aereniphaula bandana sp. nov., 10, Aereniphaula machadorum." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/265667/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="561">
Fig. 
<number box="[1144,1160,1483,1507]" pageId="6" pageNumber="561" value="9.0">9</number>
</figureCitation>
), and by the pattern of pubescence. In 
<taxonomicName box="[326,507,1518,1542]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Aereniphaula" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="561" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="machadorum">
<emphasis box="[326,507,1518,1542]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="561">A. machadorum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the distance between the upper lobes is equal to the width of an upper lobe (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURES 4 – 10. 4 – 7" captionStartId="7.[151,264,1598,1620]" captionTargetBox="[151,1434,176,1573]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[151,1436,157,1577]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 4 – 10. 4 – 7, Aereniphaula bandana sp. nov., holotype, male, 4, dorsal view, 5, ventral view, 6, lateral view, 7, detail of head and pronotum; 8, Aereniphaula machadorum, detail of head and pronotum; 9 – 10, detail of metatarsomere I, 9, Aereniphaula bandana sp. nov., 10, Aereniphaula machadorum." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/265667/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="561">
Fig. 
<number box="[151,166,1555,1579]" pageId="6" pageNumber="561" value="8.0">8</number>
</figureCitation>
); the prothorax has the same width at the anterior and posterior margins; and metatarsomere I is twice the length of II–III combined (
<figureCitation box="[374,458,1590,1615]" captionStart="FIGURES 4 – 10. 4 – 7" captionStartId="7.[151,264,1598,1620]" captionTargetBox="[151,1434,176,1573]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[151,1436,157,1577]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 4 – 10. 4 – 7, Aereniphaula bandana sp. nov., holotype, male, 4, dorsal view, 5, ventral view, 6, lateral view, 7, detail of head and pronotum; 8, Aereniphaula machadorum, detail of head and pronotum; 9 – 10, detail of metatarsomere I, 9, Aereniphaula bandana sp. nov., 10, Aereniphaula machadorum." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/265667/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="561">
Fig. 
<number box="[427,458,1591,1615]" pageId="6" pageNumber="561" value="10.0">10</number>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
